; D5 recursive-negate fixture (checkpoint (d), analysis sec 4.5 R9).
;
; A negate lives INSIDE a recursive SCC: reach's inductive rule carries
; !dead(Y). This is the shape the D5' deletion argument claims is
; unreachable through BuildEagerNegateRegion (the negate CanProduceDeletions,
; so the eager walk cuts before it) and instead exercises:
;   - the R2 fixpoint-context negate gate (kInNew both signs on refire), and
;   - the recursive crossover class (RuleClass over the negate's own table,
;     folded from the differential `dead` frontier),
; because `dead` is @differential (both crossover arms live).
;
; reach(X)   : src(X).                         base
; reach(Y)   : reach(X), edge(X, Y), !dead(Y). inductive, negate on the cycle
;
; Chain src=1, edges 1->2->3->4. With dead empty, reach = {1,2,3,4}.
; Flipping dead(3) on kills reach(3) AND (transitively) reach(4): a negated
; key deletion must propagate through the recursive SCC, not just one hop.
; Flipping dead(3) back off must re-derive both.
;
; Oracle-verified end states (analysis sec 4.5 R9):
;   after batch 1: reach = {1,2,3,4}
;   after batch 2: reach = {1,2}          (+dead 3 kills 3 and 4)
;   after batch 3: reach = {1,2,3,4}      (-dead 3 restores both)
;   after batch 4: reach = {1,2,3,4}      (churn: +dead 3 / -dead 3 nets zero)
#message src(u64 X).
#message edge(u64 From, u64 To).
#message dead(u64 X) @differential.

#local reach(X).

#query reach_out(free u64 X).

reach(X) : src(X).
reach(Y) : reach(X), edge(X, Y), !dead(Y).

reach_out(X) : reach(X).
